uent mail, 1928-1938, as well as bills and petitions. The collection reveals a great deal about life in South Carolina during the Great Depression, particularly regarding politics, elections, and appointments. Other topics covered include Gasque’s opposition to the local Republican regime and his attempts to influence patronage, as well as his efforts to expand the Inland Waterway (now called Intracoastal Waterway) through his district, in response to constituent complaints about flood devastation suffered by local farmers in the fall of 1928 and 1929. Further information and finding aid available at: http://www.sc.edu/library/scpc/gasque.html.","recordLocation":{"name":"South Carolina Political Collections","location":{"addressLocality":"Columbia","addressRegion":"SC"},"parentRecordLocation":{"name":"University of South Carolina","location":{"addressLocality":"Columbia","addressRegion":"SC"}}}},{"name":"In the Daniel C. Roper Papers, 1860-1958, 56 linear feet.","recordType":["Papers"],"description":"Persons represented include Allard Gasque.","recordLocation":{"name":"Rare Book, Manuscript, and Special Collections Library","location":{"addressLocality":"Durham","addressRegion":"NC"},"parentRecordLocation":{"name":"Duke University Libraries","location":{"addressLocality":"Durham","addressRegion":"NC"}}}}]}
